I Almost Quit My First Day:

My First Leap as a Fractional CTO

 Left the full-time gig behind and jumped straight into the fire. First job as a Fractional CTO?

A complete rebuild of the tech stack. Not long after leaving the comforts of FTE...

everything I feared came true.

Here's how it went down:

 Everything needed to be rebuilt... from the ground up.
 I almost quit.
 Grounded myself.
 And then I almost quit again.
 So I decided to go full Neo...

The emotional rollercoaster was real:

 The "how" almost broke me...

 Understanding I can only control how I react.

 Their CEO was... unhinged.

 Most of the team was crushing it, just needed a clear vision and sound architecture.

 I reminded myself "Why", and followed the rabbit.
In the end?


In the end? Rebuilt the tech stack, optimized their performance, increased their time to market, and... got a referral. 

Sometimes, our inner monologue shapes our reality, for better or worse.

If I had kept saying to myself, "Why the f*** am I doing this? I should just quit" I wonder where I‚Äôd be right now‚Ä¶

Ever feel like giving up was the easier path? What kept you going?

comments.commentText: I was in the same situation and didn't quit. This is what helps us to grow. Thanks for sharing your story!

Success isn't about knowing it all.

EQ, not IQ, shapes the way you lead and live.

The secret to meaningful leadership isn‚Äôt just knowledge or titles.

It‚Äôs your ability to connect, empathize, and stay grounded.

Here‚Äôs how emotional intelligence plays out daily:

1. You create space for others to shine.
‚Ü≥ Success is a shared journey, not a solo climb.

2. You remain steady when deadlines approach.
‚Ü≥ Respond to pressure with presence, not panic.

3. You address mistakes with curiosity, not blame.
‚Ü≥ Focus on solutions and mutual growth.

4. You carve out time to reflect and recharge.
‚Ü≥ Protecting your energy is key to showing up fully.

5. You notice and celebrate small wins on the team.
‚Ü≥ Gratitude keeps motivation alive.

6. You step back to process frustration instead of reacting.
‚Ü≥ A pause is powerful when emotions run high.

7. You seek feedback and use it to improve.
‚Ü≥ Growth starts with humility.

8. You empathize with someone else's struggle.
‚Ü≥ Active listening builds unshakable relationships.

9. You sense when a teammate feels overwhelmed.
‚Ü≥ Offer help before they ask‚Äîit builds trust.

10. You clarify expectations to prevent misunderstandings.
‚Ü≥ Clear communication is respect in action.

11. You acknowledge when you don‚Äôt know the answer.
‚Ü≥ Vulnerability inspires confidence and connection.

12. You let go of past mistakes‚Äîyours and others'.
‚Ü≥ Forgiveness is freedom.

Emotional intelligence is like a muscle.

The more you practice, the stronger it grows.

posts.content:
Anyone else feeling concerned right now? 

I have been reading about the recent decisions by companies likeandto scale back their Diversity, Equity and Inclusion (DEI) programmes.

Inclusion is something I view as vital not only in business, but in society.

Looking ahead, surely this ‚Äúscaling back‚Äù has the potential to lead to multiple harmful outcomes:

Reduced workforce diversity - which in turn may limit the variety of perspectives and ideas which are essential for innovation and problem-solving.

Damage to company reputation - especially amongst consumers and business partners who prioritise DEI and social responsibility (perhaps these businesses are so big that it doesn‚Äôt matter‚Ä¶)

 Decreased employee morale and engagement - particularly from underrepresented groups and their allies.

 Legal and compliance risks - in relation to equality, which may leave businesses exposed to claims of discrimination.

 Increased turnover rates - a costly and time-consuming issue to remedy.

‚Äôs full article can be found here 



I know I‚Äôm not the only person who feels uneasy about all of this.

To quote, author of ‚ÄúUnwavering‚Äù and a prominent DEI advocate:

"Diversity is a fact, but inclusion is a choice we make every day. As leaders, we have to put out the message that we embrace, and not just tolerate, diversity."

Like many others, I will watch this space with trepidation.

In the meantime,will continue to champion change, raise awareness and keep building an inclusive culture.



[ Image is taken from an article in The Guardian from 10 January. It shows a man in a blue t-shirt called Mark Zuckerberg with the headline ‚ÄúMeta terminates its DEI programs days before Trump inauguration.‚Äù]

comments.commentText:
I think we need to change the ‚Äúcharged‚Äù narrative around DEI. 

Those that consider it woke have jumped on it as a divisive, specific agenda-led initiative. 

However from where I sit - at its core - it is about taking the time to think about and understand humans from different backgrounds, heritages, communities. To enable us to attract, develop and grow the best talent. This leads to diversity of people and even more important - diversity of thought/ideas that will grow your business.

Who wants to shut that down?

Jonathan Worrell thank you so much for this measured and constructive comment, that is exactly how I feel and why I am concerned about the direction of travel. I really appreciate you sharing your perspective.
Sophie Wardell it‚Äôs reassuring to find others feeling the same! We need to keep showing the true value of DEI to business

We‚Äôre heading for a global reduced workforce! We already have a declining birth rate and 9.3 million people are inactive in the UK, mainly because they are being locked out of employment due to caring responsibilities & health issues. Every day 600 carers leave the workplace () and 47% of part-timers are women over 40 ().

We‚Äôve already since a decline in part-time & role share opportunities during the past decade. Now we‚Äôre seeing a decline in remote & hybrid working. All of these options are essential to attract & retain a diverse talent pool across a multigenerational workforce.

Offering a wide choice of flexible working options including part-time isn‚Äôt limited to DEI programmes. Most people across all age groups now need to work flexibly or part-time for a number of different reasons. These include family, parental & caring responsibilities, a portfolio career with self-employment or other contracts, study & research, regular voluntary & community work, health issues or a disabilty or to spend time on personal interests and projects.

The idea of working a full-time 5 day week onsite in the same role belongs to the 20th century. People now need other options to fit in with their commitments and needs.

Alison Curtis - Chartered MCIPD agreed - linging to outdated, rigid work structures ignores the evolving needs of a multigenerational workforce and risks losing valuable talent. Flexibility benefits everyone, not just those traditionally supported by DEI programmes.
